Data streaming operations consume a significant portion of CPU resources in data centers. The Data Streaming Accelerator (DSA), integrated into modern Intel CPUs in datacenter, offers promising acceleration for these operations with user-friendly features. However, previous studies have overlooked DSA's internal mechanisms and the performance implications of these features, leaving key performance issues unresolved in real-world usage. In this paper, we conduct an in-depth analysis of DSA, focusing on five previously overlooked internal mechanisms that significantly impact performance, and summarize seven design principle insights for efficient DSA utilization. Based on these insights, we introduce LightDSA, a user-friendly, asynchronous DSA library featuring low-overhead, run-to-completion optimizations. Evaluations demonstrate that our LightDSA achieves up to 3× improvement in microbenchmarks and achieves 23.6% speedup in an end-to-end Redis case study compared to direct DSA usage, highlighting the power of hardware-aware, transparent optimization in enabling efficient DSA for practical use.